# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apple-wine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apple-wine/apfelwein] In the Frankfurt area, berries from the service tree (*Sorbus domestica*) may be added in small quantities to increase astringency, in which case the specific type of *Apfelwein* is called *Speierling*.
[src:apple-wine/apfelwein] In modern times, the term *Speierling* is often also used to refer to any more sour variety of Apfelwein, even if it lacks any juice of the service tree.
[src:apple-wine/apfelwein] Most establishments also serve *Apfelwein* by the *Bembel* (a specific *Apfelwein* jug), much like how beer can be purchased by the pitcher in many countries.
[src:apple-wine/apfelwein] The paunchy *Bembel* (made from salt-glazed stoneware) usually has a basic grey colour with blue-painted detailing.
[src:apple-wine/apfelwein] In the Eifel region, near Hunsrück, around Moseltal, along the lower Saar and in Trier, the drinking container is called *Viezporz* and consists of white porcelain or stoneware.
[src:apple-wine/apfelwein] Hot *Apfelwein* is commonly taken as an old household remedy against colds, or as a warming beverage in the cold season.
[src:apple-wine/apfelwein] The *Apfelwein* is heated and served with a cinnamon stick, possibly with cloves and a slice of orange, much like mulled wine.
[src:apple-wine/apfelwein] An official *Viez* route, (*Route du Cidre*) connects Saarburg with the border to Luxembourg.
[src:apple-wine/apfelwein] An annual *Viez Fest* is celebrated in Merzig.
[src:apple-wine/apfelwein] The date is usually the second Saturday in October.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] English is either the official language, or one of the official languages, of 57 sovereign states and 30 dependent territories, making it the most geographically widespread language in the world.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] In the United Kingdom, the United States, Australia, and New Zealand, it is the dominant language for historical reasons without being explicitly defined by law.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] It is a co‑official language of the United Nations, the European Union, and many other international and regional organisations.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] It has also become the *de facto* lingua franca of diplomacy, science, technology, international trade, logistics, tourism, aviation, entertainment, and the Internet.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] *Ethnologue* estimated that there were over 1.4 billion speakers worldwide as of 2021.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Old English emerged from a group of West Germanic dialects spoken by the Anglo-Saxons.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Early inscriptions were written with runes before a Latin‑based alphabet was adopted for longer texts.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Late Old English borrowed some grammar and core vocabulary from Old Norse, a North Germanic language.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] An evolution of the Latin alphabet, the English alphabet, fully supplanted the runic alphabet by the High Middle Ages, coinciding with the emergence of Middle English in England under Norman control.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Middle English borrowed vocabulary extensively from French dialects, which are the source of approximately 28 per cent of Modern English words, and from Latin, which is the source of an additional 28 per cent.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] While Latin and the Romance languages are thus the source for a majority of its lexicon taken as a whole, English's grammar and phonology remain Germanic, as does most of its basic everyday vocabulary.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Finally, Middle English transformed, in part through the Great Vowel Shift, into Modern English, which exists on a dialect continuum with Scots; it is next most closely related to Low Saxon and Frisian.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] English is a member of the Indo-European language family, belonging to the West Germanic branch of Germanic languages.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Old English was one of several Ingvaeonic languages, which emerged from a dialect continuum spoken by West Germanic peoples during the 5th century in Frisia, on the coast of the North Sea.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Old English emerged among the Ingvaeonic speakers on the British Isles following their migration to the region, while the other Ingvaeonic languages (Frisian and Old Low German) developed in parallel on the European continent.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Old English evolved into Middle English, which in turn evolved into Modern English.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Particular dialects of Old and Middle English also developed into other Anglic languages, including Scots and the extinct Fingallian and Yola dialects of Ireland.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] English was isolated from other Germanic languages on the continent and diverged considerably in vocabulary, syntax, and phonology as a result.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] It is not mutually intelligible with any continental Germanic language – though some, such as Dutch and Frisian, share strong affinities with it, particularly in its earlier stages.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] English and Frisian were traditionally considered more closely related to one another than they were to other West Germanic languages, but most modern scholarship does not recognise a particular affinity between them.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Though they shared similar sound changes that were found nowhere else around the North Sea at that time, the specific changes appeared in English and Frisian at different times – a pattern that is uncharacteristic of languages that share a unique phylogenetic ancestor.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Old English (also called *Anglo-Saxon*) was the earliest form of the English language, spoken from c.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Old English developed from a set of West Germanic dialects, sometimes identified as Anglo-Frisian or North Sea Germanic, originally spoken along the coasts of Frisia, Lower Saxony and southern Jutland by the Germanic peoples known from historical records as the Angles, Saxons, and Jutes.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] From the 5th century, the Anglo-Saxons settled Britain as the Roman economy and administration collapsed.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] By the 7th century, Old English had become dominant in Britain – replacing the Common Brittonic and British Latin previously spoken during the Roman occupation, which left little influence on English.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] *England* and *English* (originally *Ænglaland* and *Ænglisc*) are both named after the Angles.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Old English was divided into two Anglian dialects (Mercian and Northumbrian) and two Saxon dialects (Kentish and West Saxon).
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Through the influence of the kingdom of Wessex and the educational reforms instated by King Alfred during the 9th century, the West Saxon dialect became the standard written variety.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] The epic poem *Beowulf* is written in West Saxon, and the earliest English poem, *Cædmon's Hymn*, is written in Northumbrian.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Modern English developed mainly from Mercian, but the Scots language developed from Northumbrian.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] During the earliest period of Old English, a few short inscriptions were made using a runic alphabet.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] By the 7th century, a Latin alphabet had been adopted.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Written with half-uncial letterforms, it included the runic letters *wynn* ⟨*ƿ*⟩ and *thorn* ⟨*þ*⟩, and the modified Latin letters *eth* ⟨*ð*⟩ and *ash* ⟨*æ*⟩.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Old English is markedly different from Modern English; 21st‑century English speakers are entirely unable to understand Old English without special training.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Its grammar was similar to that of modern German: nouns, adjectives, pronouns, and verbs had many more inflectional endings and forms, and word order was much freer than in Modern English.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Modern English has case forms in pronouns (*he*, *him*, *his*) and a few verb inflections (*speak*, *speaks*, *speaking*, *spoke*, *spoken*), but Old English had case endings in nouns as well, and verbs had more person and number endings.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Between the 8th and 11th centuries, the English spoken in some regions underwent significant changes due to contact with Old Norse, a North Germanic language.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Several waves of Norsemen colonising the northern British Isles in the 8th and 9th centuries brought Old English speakers into constant contact with Old Norse.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Norse influence was strongest in the north‑eastern varieties of Old English spoken in the Danelaw surrounding York; today these features are still particularly evident in Scots and Northern English.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] The centre of Norse influence was Lindsey, located in the Midlands.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] After Lindsey was incorporated into the Anglo‑Saxon polity in 920, English spread extensively throughout the region.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] One element of Norse influence that persists in all English varieties today is the third‑person pronoun group beginning with *th-* (*they*, *them*, *their*), which replaced the Anglo‑Saxon pronouns with *h-* (*hie, him, hera*).
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Other Norse loanwords include *give*, *get*, *sky*, *skirt*, *egg*, and *cake*, typically displacing a native Anglo‑Saxon equivalent.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Old Norse in this era remained largely mutually intelligible with some dialects of Old English, particularly northern ones.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] The Middle English period is often defined as beginning with the Norman Conquest in 1066.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] During the centuries that followed, English was heavily influenced by the form of Old French spoken by the new Norman ruling class that had migrated to England (known as Old Norman).
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Over the following decades of contact, members of the middle and upper classes, whether native English or Norman, became increasingly bilingual.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] By 1150 at the latest, bilingual speakers represented a majority of the English aristocracy, and monolingual French speakers were nearly non‑existent.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] The French spoken by the Norman elite in England eventually developed into the Anglo‑Norman language.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] The transition from Old to Middle English can also be placed during the composition of the *Ormulum* (c. late 12th century), a work by the Augustinian canon Orrm which highlights the blending of Old English and Anglo‑Norman elements in the language for the first time.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] As the lower classes, who represented the vast majority of the population, remained monolingual English speakers, the primary influence of Norman was as a lexical superstratum, introducing a wide range of loanwords related to politics, legislation, and prestigious social domains.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] For instance, the French word *trône* appears for the first time, from which the English word *throne* is derived.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Middle English also greatly simplified the inflectional system, probably in order to reconcile Old Norse and Old English, which were inflectionally different but morphologically similar.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] The distinction between nominative and accusative cases was lost except in personal pronouns; the instrumental case was dropped; and the use of the genitive case was limited to indicating possession.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] The inflectional system regularised many irregular inflectional forms, and gradually simplified the system of agreement, making word order less flexible.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Middle English literature includes Geoffrey Chaucer's *Canterbury Tales* (c.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] During the Middle English period, the use of regional dialects in writing proliferated, and dialect traits were even used for effect by authors such as Chaucer.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] In the first translation of the entire Bible into English by John Wycliffe (1382), Matthew 8:20 reads: "Foxis han dennes, and briddis of heuene han nestis." Here the plural suffix *-n* on the verb *have* is still retained, but none of the case endings on the nouns are present.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] The period of Early Modern English, lasting from 1500 to 1700, was characterised by the Great Vowel Shift (1350–1700), inflectional simplification, and linguistic standardisation.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] The Great Vowel Shift affected the stressed long vowels of Middle English.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] It was a chain shift, meaning that each shift triggered a subsequent shift in the vowel system.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Mid and open vowels were raised, and close vowels were broken into diphthongs.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] For example, the word *bite* was originally pronounced as the word *beet* is today, and the second vowel in the word *about* was pronounced as the word *boot* is today.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] The Great Vowel Shift explains many irregularities in spelling, since English retains many spellings from Middle English, and it also explains why English vowel letters have very different pronunciations from the same letters in other languages.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] English began to rise in prestige relative to Norman French during the reign of Henry V.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Around 1430, the Court of Chancery in Westminster began using English in its official documents, and a new standard form of Middle English, known as Chancery Standard, developed from the dialects of London and the East Midlands.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] In 1476, William Caxton introduced the printing press to England and began publishing the first printed books in London, thereby expanding the influence of this form of English.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Literature in Early Modern English includes the works of William Shakespeare and the 1611 King James Version (KJV) of the Bible.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Even after the vowel shift, the language still sounded different from Modern English: for example, the consonant clusters /kn ɡn sw/ in *knight*, *gnat*, and *sword* were still pronounced.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Many of the grammatical features that a modern reader of Shakespeare might find quaint or archaic represent the distinct characteristics of Early Modern English.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] By the late 18th century, the British Empire had spread English through its colonies and geopolitical dominance.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Commerce, science and technology, diplomacy, art, and formal education all contributed to English becoming the first truly global language.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] English also facilitated worldwide international communication.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] English was adopted in parts of North America, parts of Africa, Oceania, and many other regions.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] When they obtained political independence, some of the newly independent states that had multiple indigenous languages opted to continue using English as the official language, in order to avoid the political and other difficulties inherent in promoting any one indigenous language above the others.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] In the 20th century, the growing economic and cultural influence of the United States and its status as a superpower following the Second World War – along with worldwide broadcasting in English by the BBC and other broadcasters – has caused the language to spread across the planet much faster.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] In 1951, the International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO) recommended to the International Chicago Convention that Aviation English be universally adopted for "international aeronautical radiotelephony communications".
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] In 2001, the International Maritime Organization (IMO) developed a set of key phrases, named Standard Marine Communication Phrases (SMCP), in English, to be the recognised language supported by the international maritime community for use at sea.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] In the 21st century, English is more widely spoken and written than any other language in history.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] As Modern English developed, explicit norms for standard usage were published and spread through official media such as public education and state‑sponsored publications.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] In 1755, Samuel Johnson published his *Dictionary of the English Language*, which introduced standard spellings of words and usage norms.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] In 1828, Noah Webster published the *American Dictionary of the English Language* to establish a norm for speaking and writing American English independent of the British standard.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Within Britain, non‑standard or lower‑class dialect features were increasingly stigmatised, leading to the rapid spread of the prestige varieties among the middle classes.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] In modern English, the loss of grammatical case is almost complete (it is now found only in pronouns, such as *he* and *him*, *she* and *her*, *who* and *whom*), and subject–verb–object word order is largely fixed.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Some changes, such as the use of *do*-support, have become universalised.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] (Earlier English did not use the word *do* as a general auxiliary as Modern English does; at first it was used only in question constructions, and even then it was not obligatory.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Now, *do*-support with the verb *have* is becoming increasingly standardised.) The use of progressive forms ending in *-ing* appears to be spreading to new constructions, and forms such as "had been being built" are becoming more common.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Regularisation of irregular forms also continues slowly (e.g.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] *dreamed* instead of *dreamt*), and analytical alternatives to inflectional forms are becoming more common (e.g.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] British English is also undergoing change under the influence of American English, fuelled by the strong presence of American English in the media.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] As of 2016, 400 million people spoke English as their first language, and 1.1 billion spoke it as a second language.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] English is the largest language by number of speakers, spoken by communities on every continent.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Estimates of second‑language and foreign‑language speakers vary greatly depending on how proficiency is defined, ranging from 470 million to more than 1 billion.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] In 2003, David Crystal estimated that non‑native speakers outnumbered native speakers by a ratio of three to one.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Braj Kachru has categorised countries into the Three Circles of English model, according to how the language historically spread in each country, how it is acquired by the population, and the range of uses it has there – with a country's classification being able to change over time.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] 'Inner‑circle' countries have large communities of native English speakers; these include the United Kingdom, the United States, Australia, Canada, Ireland, and New Zealand (where the majority speaks English), as well as South Africa (where a significant minority speaks English).
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] The countries with the most native English speakers are, in descending order: the United States (at least 231 million), the United Kingdom (60 million), Canada (19 million), Australia (at least 17 million), South Africa (4.8 million), Ireland (4.2 million), and New Zealand (3.7 million).
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] In these countries, children of native speakers learn English from their parents; citizens with other first languages, as well as incoming immigrants, learn English in order to communicate in local English‑speaking neighbourhoods and workplaces.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Inner‑circle countries are the base from which English spreads to other regions of the world.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] These countries have millions of native speakers on dialect continua, which range from English-based creole languages to standard varieties of English used in inner‑circle countries.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] They have many more speakers who acquire English as they grow up through day‑to‑day use and exposure to English‑language broadcasting, especially if they attend schools where English is the language of instruction.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] 'Expanding‑circle' countries are those where English is taught as a foreign language, though the character of English as a first, second, or foreign language in a given country is often debatable and may change over time.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] For example, in countries such as the Netherlands, an overwhelming majority of the population can speak English, and it is often used in higher education and to communicate with foreigners.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] English is a pluricentric language, which means that no single national authority sets the standard for its use.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Spoken English, including English used in broadcasting, generally follows national pronunciation standards that are established by custom rather than by regulation.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] International broadcasters are usually identifiable as coming from one country rather than another through their accents, but newsreader scripts are also composed largely in international standard written English.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] The norms of standard written English are maintained purely by the consensus of educated English speakers around the world, without any oversight by any government or international organisation.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] American listeners readily understand most British broadcasting, and British listeners readily understand most American broadcasting.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Most English speakers around the world can understand radio programmes, television programmes, and films from many parts of the English-speaking world.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Both standard and non‑standard varieties of English can include formal or informal styles, distinguished by word choice and syntax, and they use both technical and non‑technical registers.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] The settlement history of the English‑speaking inner‑circle countries outside Britain helped to level dialect distinctions and produce koiné forms of English in South Africa, Australia, and New Zealand.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] The majority of immigrants to the United States without British ancestry rapidly adopted English after arrival.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Now the majority of the United States population are monolingual English speakers.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Modern English is sometimes described as the first global lingua franca, or as the first world language.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] English is the world's most widely used language in newspaper publishing, book publishing, international telecommunications, scientific publishing, international trade, mass entertainment, and diplomacy.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Parity with French as a language of diplomacy had been achieved by the Treaty of Versailles negotiations in 1919.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] By the time the United Nations was founded at the end of the Second World War, English had become pre‑eminent; it is one of the six official languages of the United Nations and is now the main worldwide language of diplomacy and international relations.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Many other worldwide international organisations, including the International Olympic Committee, specify English as a working language or official language of the organisation.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] While the EU allows member states to designate any of the national languages as an official language of the Union, in practice English is the main working language of EU organisations.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] English serves as the basis for the required controlled natural languages Seaspeak and Airspeak, used as international languages of seafaring and aviation.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] English is the most frequently taught foreign language in the world.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Most people learning English do so for practical reasons, as opposed to ideological ones.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] In EU countries, English is the most widely spoken foreign language in 19 of the 25 member states where it is not an official language (that is, the countries other than Ireland and Malta).
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] In a 2012 official Eurobarometer poll (conducted when the UK was still a member of the EU), 38 per cent of EU respondents outside the countries where English is an official language said they could speak English well enough to have a conversation in that language.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] The next most commonly mentioned foreign language, French (which is the most widely known foreign language in the UK and Ireland), could be used in conversation by 12 per cent of respondents.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Working knowledge of English has become a requirement in a number of occupations and professions, such as medicine and computing.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Though it formerly had parity with French and German in scientific research, English now dominates the field.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] As decolonisation proceeded throughout the British Empire in the 1950s and 1960s, former colonies often did not reject English but rather continued to use it as independent countries setting their own language policies.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] For example, English is one of the official languages of India.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Many Indians have shifted from associating the language with colonialism to associating it with economic progress.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] English is widely used in media and literature, with India being the third‑largest publisher of English‑language books in the world, after the US and the UK.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] However, fewer than 5 per cent of the population speak English fluently, with the country's native English speakers numbering in the low hundreds of thousands.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] In 2004, David Crystal claimed that India had the largest population of people able to speak or understand English in the world, though most scholars estimate that the US remains home to a larger English‑speaking population.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Many English speakers in Africa have become part of an 'Afro‑Saxon' language community that unites Africans from different countries.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Regarding its future development, it is considered most likely that English will continue to function as a koiné language, with a standard form that unifies speakers around the world.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Dialectologists identify many English dialects, which usually refer to regional varieties that differ from each other in terms of patterns of grammar, vocabulary, and pronunciation.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] The pronunciation of particular areas distinguishes dialects as separate regional accents.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] The major native dialects of English are often divided by linguists into two extremely general categories: British English (BrE) and North American English (NAE).
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] The fact that English has been spoken in England for 1,500 years explains why England has a great wealth of regional dialects.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Within the United Kingdom, Received Pronunciation (RP), an educated accent associated originally with South East England, has been traditionally used as a broadcast standard and is considered the most prestigious of British accents.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] The spread of RP (also known as BBC English) through the media has caused many traditional dialects of rural England to recede, as youths adopt the traits of the prestige variety instead of those from local dialects.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] At the time of the 1950–61 Survey of English Dialects, grammar and vocabulary differed across the country, but a process of lexical attrition has led most of this variation to disappear.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Nonetheless, this attrition has mostly affected dialectal variation in grammar and vocabulary.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Only 3% of the English population actually speak RP, with the remainder speaking in regional accents and dialects with varying degrees of RP influence.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] There is also variability within RP, particularly along class lines between upper‑ and middle‑class RP speakers, and between native RP speakers and those who adopt RP later in life.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Within Britain, there is also considerable variation along lines of social class; some traits, though exceedingly common, are nonetheless considered 'non‑standard' and associated with lower‑class speakers and identities.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] An example of this is *h*-dropping, which was historically a feature of lower‑class London English, particularly Cockney, and can now be heard in the local accents of most parts of England.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] However, it remains largely absent from broadcasting and among the upper crust of British society.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] English in England can be divided into four major dialect regions: South East English, South West English (also known as West Country English), Midlands English, and Northern English.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Having been the centre of Danish occupation during the Viking invasions of England, Northern English dialects, particularly the Yorkshire dialect, retain Norse features not found in other English varieties.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] In the West Midlands, dialects such as Black Country (Yam Yam), and to a lesser extent Birmingham (Brummie), preserve archaic features from Early Modern and Middle English, retaining Germanic elements such as specific grammatical structures and vocabulary.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Since the 15th century, South East England varieties have centred on London, which has been the centre from which dialectal innovations have spread to other dialects.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] In London, the Cockney dialect was traditionally used by the lower classes, and it was long a socially stigmatised variety.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] The spread of Cockney features across the South East led the media to talk of Estuary English as a new dialect, but the notion was criticised by many linguists on the grounds that London had been influencing neighbouring regions throughout history.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Scots is today considered a separate language from English, but it has its origins in early Northern Middle English and developed and changed during its history with influence from other sources, particularly Scottish Gaelic and Old Norse.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Scots itself has a number of regional dialects.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] In addition to Scots, Scottish English comprises the varieties of Standard English spoken in Scotland; most varieties are Northern English accents, with some influence from Scots.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] In Ireland, various forms of English have been spoken following the Norman invasion of the island during the 11th century.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] In County Wexford and the area surrounding Dublin, two extinct dialects known as Forth and Bargy and Fingallian developed as offshoots from Early Middle English and were spoken until the 19th century.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Modern Irish English, however, has its roots in English colonisation in the 17th century.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Today Irish English is divided into Ulster English (the Northern Ireland dialect with strong influence from Scots) and various other dialects of Ireland.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Like Scottish and most North American accents, almost all Irish accents preserve the rhoticity that has been lost in the dialects influenced by RP.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Due to the relatively strong degree of mixing, mutual accommodation, and koinéisation that occurred during the colonial period, North American English has traditionally been perceived as relatively homogeneous, at least in comparison with British dialects.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] However, modern scholars have strongly opposed this notion, arguing that North American English shows a great deal of phonetic, lexical, and geographic variability.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] This becomes all the more apparent considering social, ethnolinguistic, and regional varieties such as African-American English, Chicano English, Cajun English, or Newfoundland English.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Canadian English varieties, excepting those from Atlantic Canada and possibly Quebec, are generally considered to belong to the GA continuum, although they often show raising of the vowels /aɪ/ and /aʊ/ before voiceless consonants and have distinct norms for writing and pronunciation as well.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Atlantic Canadian English, notably distinct from Standard Canadian English, comprises Maritime English and Newfoundland English.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] It was influenced mostly by British and Irish English, as well as Irish, Scottish Gaelic, and Acadian French.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] In most American and Canadian English dialects, rhoticity (or *r*-fullness) is dominant, with non-rhoticity (or *r*-dropping) being associated with lower prestige and social class, especially since the end of World War II.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] This contrasts with the situation in England, where non-rhoticity has become the standard.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Varieties beyond GA which have developed distinct sound systems include the Southern American English, New York City English, Eastern New England English, and African-American Vernacular English (AAVE) groups – all of which are historically non-rhotic, save a few varieties of Southern American.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] In Southern American English, the most populous grouping outside GA, rhoticity now strongly prevails, replacing the region's historical non-rhotic prestige.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Spoken primarily by working- and middle-class African Americans, African-American Vernacular English (AAVE) is largely non-rhotic, and likely originated among enslaved Africans and African Americans influenced primarily by the non-standard older Southern dialects.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] A minority of linguists, contrarily, propose that AAVE mostly traces back to African languages spoken by the slaves who had to develop a pidgin or English-based creole to communicate with slaves of other ethnic and linguistic origins.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] AAVE's important commonalities with Southern accents suggest it developed into a highly coherent and homogeneous variety in the 19th or early 20th century.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] AAVE is commonly stigmatised in North America as a form of "broken" or "uneducated" English, as are white Southern accents, but linguists today recognise both as fully developed varieties of English with their own norms shared by large speech communities.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Since 1788, English has been spoken in Oceania, and Australian English has developed as the first language of the vast majority of the inhabitants of the Australian continent, its standard accent being General Australian.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] The English of neighbouring New Zealand has, to a lesser degree, become an influential standard variety of the language.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Australian and New Zealand English are each other's closest relatives, with few differentiating characteristics, followed by South African English and the English of South East England, all of which have similarly non‑rhotic accents (aside from some accents in the South Island of New Zealand).
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Australian and New Zealand English stand out for their innovative vowels: many short vowels are fronted or raised, whereas many long vowels have been diphthongised.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Australian English also has a contrast between long and short vowels that is not found in most other varieties.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Australian English grammar aligns closely with British and American English; like American English, collective plural subjects take a singular verb – for example, "the government is" (rather than 'are').
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] New Zealand English uses front vowels that are often even higher than those in Australian English.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] English is an official language of the Philippines.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Its use is ubiquitous in the country, appearing on street signs, marquees, and government documents, as well as in courtrooms, public media, the entertainment industry, and the business sector.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] It became an important and widely spoken language in the country during the period of American rule between 1898 and 1946.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Taglish is a prominent form of code-switching between Tagalog and English.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] English is spoken widely in southern Africa and is an official or co‑official language in several of the region's countries.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] In South Africa, English has been spoken since 1820, co‑existing with Afrikaans and various African languages such as the Khoe and Bantu languages.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Today, about nine per cent of the South African population speaks South African English (SAE) as a first language.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] SAE is a non‑rhotic variety that tends to follow RP as a norm.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] It is one of the few non‑rhotic English varieties that lack intrusive R.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] The second‑language varieties of South Africa differ according to the native languages of their speakers.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Most phonological differences from RP are in the vowels.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Consonantal differences include the tendency to pronounce /p, t, t͡ʃ, k/ without aspiration (e.g.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] *pin* pronounced [pɪn] rather than [pʰɪn] as in most other varieties), while 'r' is often pronounced as a flap [ɾ] instead of as the more common fricative.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Nigerian English is a variety of English spoken in Nigeria; over 150 million Nigerians speak some form of the language.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Though traditionally based on British English, increasing United States influence during the latter part of the 20th century has resulted in American English vocabulary entering Nigerian English.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Additionally, some new words and collocations have emerged from the variety out of a need to express concepts specific to the nation's culture (e.g.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Varieties of English are spoken throughout the former British colonial possessions in the Caribbean, including Jamaica, the Leeward and Windward Islands, Trinidad and Tobago, Barbados, the Cayman Islands, and Belize.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Each of these areas is home both to a local variety of English and a local English‑based creole, combining English and African languages.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] The most prominent varieties are Jamaican English and Jamaican Creole.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] In Central America, English‑based creoles are spoken on the Caribbean coasts of Nicaragua and Panama.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Residents are often fluent in both the local English variety and the local creole languages, and frequently code-switch between them.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] The relationship between different varieties can be conceptualised as a continuum, in which more creole‑like or RP‑like forms function as more formal and informal registers of the language respectively.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Most Caribbean varieties are based on British English and, consequently, most are non‑rhotic, except for formal styles of Jamaican English, which are often rhotic.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Jamaican English differs from RP in its vowel inventory, which has a distinction between long and short vowels rather than tense and lax vowels as in Standard English.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] The diphthongs /ei/ and /ou/ are monophthongs [eː] and [oː] or even the reverse diphthongs [ie] and [uo] (e.g.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] *bay* and *boat* pronounced [bʲeː] and [bʷoːt]).
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Often, word‑final consonant clusters are simplified so that "child" is pronounced [t͡ʃail] and "wind" [win].
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Indian English historically tends towards RP as an ideal, with the proximity of speakers to RP generally reflecting class distinctions.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Indian English accents are marked by the pronunciation of phonemes such as /t/ and /d/ (often pronounced with retroflex articulation as [ʈ] and [ɖ]) and the replacement of /θ/ and /ð/ with dentals [t̪] and [d̪].
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Sometimes Indian English speakers may also use spelling‑based pronunciations, where the silent ⟨h⟩ found in words such as *ghost* is pronounced as an Indian voiced aspirated stop [ɡʱ].
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] Non‑native English speakers may pronounce words differently because they have not fully mastered English pronunciation.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] This can happen either because they apply the speech rules of their mother tongue to English ('interference') or because they implement strategies similar to those used in first language acquisition.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p01] They may create novel pronunciations for English sounds that do not exist in their first language.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] English phonology and phonetics differ from one dialect to another, usually without interfering with mutual communication.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Phonological variation affects the inventory of phonemes (speech sounds that distinguish meaning), and phonetic variation consists in differences in pronunciation of the phonemes.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] This overview mainly describes Received Pronunciation (RP) and General American (GA), the standard varieties of the United Kingdom and the United States respectively.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Most English dialects share the same 24 consonant phonemes (or 26, if marginal /x/ and glottal stop /ʔ/ are included).
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] The consonant inventory shown below is valid for California English, and for RP.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] For pairs of obstruents (stops, affricates, and fricatives) such as /p b/, /tʃ dʒ/, and /s z/, the first is fortis (strong) and the second is lenis (weak).
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Fortis obstruents, such as /p tʃ s/ are pronounced with more muscular tension and breath force than lenis consonants, such as /b dʒ z/, and are always voiceless.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Lenis consonants are partly voiced at the beginning and end of utterances, and fully voiced between vowels.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Fortis stops such as /p/ have additional articulatory or acoustic features in most dialects: they are aspirated [pʰ] when they occur alone at the beginning of a stressed syllable, often unaspirated in other cases, and often unreleased [p̚] or pre-glottalised [ʔp] at the end of a syllable.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] In a single-syllable word, a vowel before a fortis stop is shortened: e.g.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] *nip* has a noticeably shorter vowel (phonetically, not phonemically) than *nib* [nɪˑb̥] (see below).
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] In RP, the lateral approximant /l/ has two main allophones (pronunciation variants): the clear or plain [l], as in *light*, and the dark or velarised [ɫ], as in *full*.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] All sonorants (liquids /l, r/ and nasals /m, n, ŋ/) devoice when following a voiceless obstruent, and they are syllabic when following a consonant at the end of a word.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] The pronunciation of vowels varies a great deal between dialects and is one of the most detectable aspects of a speaker's accent.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] The accompanying table below lists the vowel phonemes in RP and GA, with example words from lexical sets.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] The vowels are represented with symbols from the International Phonetic Alphabet; those given for RP are standard in British dictionaries and other publications.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] In RP, vowel length is phonemic; long vowels are marked with a triangular colon ⟨ː⟩ in the table above, such as the vowel of *need* [niːd] as opposed to *bid* [bɪd].
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Because lenis consonants are frequently voiceless at the end of a syllable, vowel length is an important cue as to whether the following consonant is lenis or fortis.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] The vowel /ə/ only occurs in unstressed syllables and is more open in quality in stem-final positions.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Some dialects do not contrast /ɪ/ and /ə/ in unstressed positions, such that *rabbit* and *abbot* rhyme and *Lenin* and *Lennon* are homophonous, a dialectal feature called the weak vowel merger.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] GA /ɜr/ and /ər/ are realised as an *r*-coloured vowel [ɚ], as in *further* [ˈfɚðɚ] (phonemically /ˈfɜrðər/), which in RP is realised as [ˈfəːðə] (phonemically /ˈfɜːðə/).
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] An English syllable includes a syllable nucleus consisting of a vowel sound.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Syllable onset and coda (start and end) are optional.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] A syllable can start with up to three consonant sounds, as in *sprint* /sprɪnt/, and end with up to five, as in (for some dialects) *angsts* /aŋksts/.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] This gives an English syllable a structure of (CCC)V(CCCCC) – where C represents a consonant and V a vowel.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] The word *strengths* /strɛŋθs/ is thus close to the most complex syllable possible in English.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] The consonants that may appear together in onsets or codas are restricted, as is the order in which they may appear.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Onsets can only have four types of consonant clusters: a stop and approximant, as in *play*; a voiceless fricative and approximant, as in *fly* or *sly*; *s* and a voiceless stop, as in *stay*; and *s*, a voiceless stop, and an approximant, as in *string*.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Clusters of nasal and stop are only allowed in codas.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Clusters of obstruents always agree in voicing, and clusters of sibilants and of plosives with the same point of articulation are prohibited.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Several consonants have limited distributions: /h/ can only occur in syllable-initial position, and /ŋ/ only in syllable-final position.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Stress plays an important role in English.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Certain syllables are stressed, while others are unstressed.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Stress is a combination of duration, intensity, vowel quality, and sometimes changes in pitch.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Stressed syllables are pronounced longer and louder than unstressed syllables, and vowels in unstressed syllables are frequently reduced while vowels in stressed syllables are not.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Stress in English is phonemic, gaining freedom and dynamicity once lost in Proto-Germanic through a majority of borrowings from non-Germanic languages.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] For instance, the word *contract* is stressed on the first syllable (/ˈkɒntrækt/ *KON-trakt*) when used as a noun, but on the last syllable (/kənˈtrækt/ *kən-TRAKT*) for most meanings (for example, "reduce in size") when used as a verb.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Here stress is connected to vowel reduction: in the noun "contract" the first syllable is stressed and has the unreduced vowel /ɒ/, but in the verb "contract" the first syllable is unstressed and its vowel is reduced to /ə/.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Stress is also used to distinguish between words and phrases, so that a compound word receives a single stress unit, but the corresponding phrase has two: e.g.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] "a burnout" (/ˈbɜːrnaʊt/) versus "to burn out" (/ˈbɜːrn ˈaʊt/), and "a hotdog" (/ˈhɒtdɒɡ/) versus "a hot dog" (/ˈhɒt ˈdɒɡ/).
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] In terms of rhythm, English is generally described as a stress-timed language, meaning that the amount of time between stressed syllables tends to be equal.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Stressed syllables are pronounced longer, but unstressed syllables (syllables between stresses) are shortened.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Vowels in unstressed syllables are shortened as well, and vowel shortening causes changes in vowel quality: vowel reduction.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Varieties of English vary the most in pronunciation of vowels.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] The best-known national varieties used as standards for education in non-English-speaking countries are British (BrE) and American (AmE).
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Countries such as Canada, Australia, Ireland, New Zealand and South Africa have their own standard varieties which are less often used as standards for education internationally.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] English has undergone many historical sound changes, some of them affecting all varieties, and others affecting only a few.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Most standard varieties are affected by the Great Vowel Shift, which changed the pronunciation of long vowels, but a few dialects have slightly different results.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] In North America, a number of chain shifts such as the Northern Cities Vowel Shift and Canadian Shift have produced very different vowel landscapes in some regional accents.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Some dialects have fewer or more consonant phonemes and phones than the standard varieties.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Some conservative varieties like Scottish English have a voiceless [ʍ] sound in *whine* that contrasts with the voiced [w] in *wine*, but most other dialects pronounce both words with voiced [w], a dialect feature called *wine*–*whine* merger.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] The voiceless velar fricative sound /x/ is found in Scottish English, which distinguishes *loch* /lɔx/ from *lock* /lɔk/.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Other changes affecting the phonology of local varieties are processes such as *yod*-dropping, *yod*-coalescence, and reduction of consonant clusters.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] GA and RP vary in their pronunciation of historical /r/ after a vowel at the end of a syllable (in the syllable coda).
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] GA is a rhotic dialect, meaning that it pronounces /r/ at the end of a syllable, but RP is non-rhotic, meaning that it loses /r/ in that position.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] English dialects are classified as rhotic or non-rhotic depending on whether they elide /r/ like RP or keep it like GA.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] There is complex dialectal variation in words with the open front and open back vowels /æ ɑː ɒ ɔː/.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] These four vowels are only distinguished in RP, Australia, New Zealand and South Africa.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] In GA, these vowels merge to three /æ ɑ ɔ/, and in Canadian English, they merge to two /æ ɑ/.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Since the 9th century, English has been written using the English alphabet, which uses the Latin script.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Anglo-Saxon runes were previously used to write Old English, but only in short inscriptions; the overwhelming majority of attested writings in Old English are in the Old English Latin alphabet.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] English orthography is multi-layered and complex, with elements of French, Latin, and Greek spelling on top of the native Germanic system.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Further complications have arisen through sound changes with which the orthography has not kept pace.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Compared to European languages for which official organisations have promoted spelling reforms, English has spelling that is a less consistent indicator of pronunciation, and standard spellings of words that are more difficult to guess from knowing how a word is pronounced.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] There are also systematic spelling differences between British and American English.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] These situations have prompted proposals for spelling reform in English.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Although letters and speech sounds do not have a one-to-one correspondence in standard English spelling, spelling rules that take into account syllable structure, phonetic changes in derived words, and word accent are reliable for most English words.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Moreover, standard English spelling shows etymological relationships between related words that would be obscured by a closer correspondence between pronunciation and spelling – for example, the words *photograph*, *photography*, and *photographic*, or the words *electricity* and *electrical*.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] While few scholars agree with Chomsky and Halle (1968) that conventional English orthography is "near-optimal", there is a rationale for current English spelling patterns.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] The standard orthography of English is the most widely used writing system in the world.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Standard English spelling is based on a graphomorphemic segmentation of words into written clues of what meaningful units make up each word.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Readers of English can generally rely on the correspondence between spelling and pronunciation to be fairly regular for letters or digraphs used to spell consonant sounds.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] The letters *c* and *g* normally represent /k/ and /ɡ/, but there is also a soft *c* pronounced /s/, and a soft *g* pronounced /dʒ/.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] The differences in the pronunciations of the letters *c* and *g* are often signalled by the following letters in standard English spelling.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Digraphs used to represent phonemes and phoneme sequences include *ch* for /tʃ/, *sh* for /ʃ/, *th* for /θ/ or /ð/, *ng* for /ŋ/, *qu* for /kw/, and *ph* for /f/ in Greek-derived words.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] The single letter *x* is generally pronounced as /z/ in word-initial position and as /ks/ otherwise.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] For the vowel sounds of the English language, however, correspondences between spelling and pronunciation are more irregular.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] There are many more vowel phonemes in English than there are single vowel letters (*a*, *e*, *i*, *o*, *u*, *y*, and very rarely *w*).
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] As a result, some "long vowels" are often indicated by combinations of letters (like the *oa* in *boat*, the *ow* in *how*, and the *ay* in *stay*), or the historically based silent *e* (as in *note* and *cake*).
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] The consequence of this complex orthographic history is that learning to read and write can be challenging in English.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] It can take longer for school pupils to become independently fluent readers of English than of many other languages, including Italian, Spanish, and German.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Nonetheless, there is an advantage for learners of English reading in learning the specific sound-symbol regularities that occur in the standard English spellings of commonly used words.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Such instruction greatly reduces the risk of children experiencing reading difficulties in English.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Making primary school teachers more aware of the primacy of morpheme representation in English may help learners learn more efficiently to read and write English.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] English writing also includes a system of punctuation marks that is similar to those used in most alphabetic languages around the world.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] The purpose of punctuation is to mark meaningful grammatical relationships in sentences to aid readers in understanding a text and to indicate features important for reading a text aloud.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Typical for an Indo-European language, English grammar follows accusative morphosyntactic alignment.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Unlike other Indo-European languages, English has largely abandoned the inflectional case system in favour of analytic constructions.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Only the personal pronouns retain morphological case more strongly than any other word class.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] English distinguishes at least seven major word classes: verbs, nouns, adjectives, adverbs, determiners (including articles), prepositions, and conjunctions.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Some analyses add pronouns as a class separate from nouns, and subdivide conjunctions into subordinators and coordinators, and add the class of interjections.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] English also has a rich set of auxiliary verbs, such as *have* and *do*, expressing the categories of mood and aspect.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Questions are marked by *do*-support, *wh*-movement (fronting of question words beginning with *wh*-) and word order inversion with some verbs.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Vestiges of the case and gender system are found in the pronoun system (*he* / *him*, *who* / *whom*); similarly, traces of more complex verb conjugation are seen in the inflection of the copula verb *to be*.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] English nouns are only inflected for number and possession.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] New nouns can be formed through derivation or compounding.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] They are semantically divided into proper nouns (names) and common nouns.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Common nouns are in turn divided into concrete and abstract nouns, and grammatically into count nouns and mass nouns.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Most count nouns are inflected for plural number through the use of the plural suffix -*s*, but a few nouns have irregular plural forms.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Mass nouns can only be pluralised through the use of a count noun classifier, e.g.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] "one loaf of bread", "two loaves of bread".
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Possession can be expressed either by the possessive enclitic -*s* (also traditionally called a genitive suffix), or by the preposition *of*.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Historically the -*s* possessive has been used for animate nouns, whereas the *of* possessive has been reserved for inanimate nouns.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Today this distinction is less clear, and many speakers use -*s* also with inanimates.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Orthographically the possessive -*s* is separated from a singular noun with an apostrophe.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] If the noun is plural formed with -*s* the apostrophe follows the -*s*.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Nouns can form noun phrases (NPs) where they are the syntactic head of the words that depend on them such as determiners, quantifiers, conjunctions or adjectives.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Noun phrases can be short, such as *the man*, composed only of a determiner and a noun.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] They can also include modifiers such as adjectives (e.g.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] *red*, *tall*, *all*) and specifiers such as determiners (e.g.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] But they can also tie together several nouns into a single long NP, using conjunctions such as *and*, or prepositions such as *with*, e.g.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] "the tall man with the long red trousers and his skinny wife with the spectacles" (this NP uses conjunctions, prepositions, specifiers, and modifiers).
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Regardless of length, an NP functions as a syntactic unit.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] For example, the possessive enclitic can, in cases which do not lead to ambiguity, follow the entire noun phrase, as in "The President of India's wife", where the enclitic follows *India* and not *President*.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] The class of determiners is used to specify the noun they precede in terms of definiteness, where *the* marks a definite noun and *a* or *an* marks an indefinite one.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] A definite noun is assumed by the speaker to be already known by the interlocutor, whereas an indefinite noun is not specified as being previously known.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Quantifiers, which include *one*, *many*, *some* and *all*, are used to specify the noun in terms of quantity or number.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] The noun must agree with the number of the determiner, e.g.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Determiners are the first constituents in a noun phrase.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] English adjectives are words such as *good*, *big*, *interesting*, and *Canadian* that most typically modify nouns, denoting characteristics of their referents (e.g.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] As modifiers, they come before the nouns they modify and after determiners.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] English adjectives also function as predicative complements (e.g.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] In Modern English, adjectives are not inflected so as to agree in form with the noun they modify, as in most other Indo-European languages.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] For example, in the phrases "the slender boy", and "many slender girls", the adjective *slender* does not change form to agree with either the number or gender of the noun.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Some adjectives are inflected for degree of comparison, with the positive degree unmarked, the suffix -*er* marking the comparative, and -*est* marking the superlative: "a small boy", "the boy is smaller than the girl", "that boy is the smallest".
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Some adjectives have irregular suppletive comparative and superlative forms, such as *good*, *better*, and *best*.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Other adjectives have comparatives formed by periphrastic constructions, with the adverb *more* marking the comparative, and *most* marking the superlative: *happier* or *more happy*, *the happiest* or *most happy*.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] There is some variation among speakers regarding which adjectives use inflected or periphrastic comparison, and some studies have shown a tendency for the periphrastic forms to become more common at the expense of the inflected form.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] English determiners are words such as *the*, *each*, *many*, *some*, and *which*, occurring most typically in noun phrases before the head nouns and any modifiers and marking the noun phrase as definite or indefinite.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] They often agree with the noun in number.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] They do not typically inflect for degree of comparison.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] English pronouns conserve many traits of case and gender inflection.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] The subjective case corresponds to the Old English nominative case, and the objective case is used in the sense both of the previous accusative case (for a patient, or direct object of a transitive verb), and of the Old English dative case (for a recipient or indirect object of a transitive verb).
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] The subjective is used when the pronoun is the subject of a finite clause, otherwise the objective is used.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Possessive pronouns exist in dependent and independent forms; the dependent form functions as a determiner specifying a noun (as in *my chair*), while the independent form can stand alone as if it were a noun (e.g.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Grammatical person in English no longer distinguishes between formal and informal pronouns of address, with the second person singular familiar pronoun *thou* that previously existed in the language having fallen almost entirely out of use by the 18th century.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Pronouns are used to refer to entities deictically or anaphorically.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] A deictic pronoun points to some person or object by identifying it relative to the speech situation – for example, the pronoun *I* identifies the speaker, and the pronoun *you*, the addressee.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Anaphoric pronouns such as *that* refer back to an entity already mentioned or assumed by the speaker to be known by the audience, for example in the sentence "I already told you that".
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] The reflexive pronouns are used when the oblique argument is identical to the subject of a phrase (e.g.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] "he sent it to himself" or "she braced herself for impact").
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Prepositional phrases (PP) are phrases composed of a preposition and one or more nouns, e.g.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] "with the dog", "for my friend", "to school", "in England".
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] English prepositions have a wide range of uses – including describing movement, place, and other relations between entities, as well as functions that are syntactic in nature, like introducing complement clauses and oblique arguments of verbs.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] For example, in the phrase "I gave it to him", the preposition *to* marks the indirect object of the verb *to give*.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Traditionally words were only considered prepositions if they governed the case of the noun they preceded, for example causing the pronouns to use the objective rather than subjective form, "with her", "to me", "for us".
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] But some contemporary grammars no longer consider government of case to be the defining feature of the class of prepositions, rather defining prepositions as words that can function as the heads of prepositional phrases.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] English verbs are inflected for tense and aspect and marked for agreement with a third person present singular subject.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Only the copula verb *to be* is still inflected for agreement with the plural and first and second person subjects.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Auxiliary verbs such as *have* and *be* are paired with verbs in the infinitive, past, or progressive forms.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] They form complex tenses, aspects, and moods.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Auxiliary verbs differ from other verbs in that they can be followed by the negation, and in that they can occur as the first constituent in a question sentence.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] The primary forms are a plain present, a third person singular present, and a preterite (past) form.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] The secondary forms are a plain form used for the infinitive, a gerund-participle and a past participle.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] The verb *to be* – which among other uses in English functions as the primary auxiliary verb indicating the imperfective aspect (e.g.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] "I *am* going"), as well as the copula – is the only verb to retain some of its original conjugation, and takes different inflectional forms depending on the subject.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] The first person present form is *am*, the third person singular form is *is*, and the form *are* is used in the second person singular and all three plurals.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] The only verb past participle is *been* and its gerund-participle is *being*.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] English has two primary tenses, past (preterite) and non-past.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] The preterite is inflected by using the preterite form of the verb, which for the regular verbs includes the suffix *-ed*, and for the strong verbs either the suffix *-t* or a change in the stem vowel.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] The non-past form is unmarked except in the third person singular, which takes the suffix *-s*.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] English does not have future verb forms.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] The future tense is expressed periphrastically with one of the auxiliary verbs *will* or *shall*.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Many varieties also use a near future constructed with the phrasal verb "be going to" (going-to future).
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Further aspectual distinctions are shown by auxiliary verbs, primarily *have* and *be*, which show the contrast between a perfect and non-perfect past tense ("I have run" vs.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] "I was running"), and compound tenses such as preterite perfect ("I had been running") and present perfect ("I have been running").
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] For the expression of mood, English uses a number of modal auxiliaries, such as *can*, *may*, *will*, *shall* and the past tense forms *could*, *might*, *would*, *should*.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] There are also subjunctive and imperative moods, both based on the plain form of the verb (i.e. without the third person singular *-s*), for use in subordinate clauses (e.g. subjunctive: "It is important that he run every day"; imperative *Run!*).
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] An infinitive form, that uses the plain form of the verb and the preposition *to*, is used for verbal clauses that are syntactically subordinate to a finite verbal clause.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Finite verbal clauses are those that are formed around a verb in the present or preterite form.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] In clauses with auxiliary verbs, they are the finite verbs and the main verb is treated as a subordinate clause.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] For example, "he has to go" where only the auxiliary verb *have* is inflected for time and the main verb *to go* is in the infinitive, or in a complement clause such as "I saw him leave", where the main verb is *see*, which is in a preterite form, and *leave* is in the infinitive.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] English also makes frequent use of constructions traditionally called phrasal verbs, verb phrases that are made up of a verb root and a preposition or particle that follows the verb.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] The phrase then functions as a single predicate.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] In terms of intonation the preposition is fused to the verb, but in writing it is written as a separate word.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Examples of phrasal verbs are "to get up", "to ask out", "to get together", and "to put up with".
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] The phrasal verb frequently has a highly idiomatic meaning that is more specialised and restricted than what can be simply extrapolated from the combination of verb and preposition complement (e.g.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] *lay off* meaning *terminate someone's employment*).
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Some grammarians do not consider this type of construction to form a syntactic constituent and hence refrain from using the term "phrasal verb".
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Instead, they consider the construction simply to be a verb with a prepositional phrase as its syntactic complement, e.g.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] "he woke up in the morning" and "he ran up in the mountains" are syntactically equivalent.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] The function of adverbs is to modify the action or event described by the verb by providing additional information about the manner in which it occurs.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Many English adverbs are derived from adjectives by appending the suffix *-ly*.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] For example, in the phrase "the woman walked quickly", the adverb *quickly* is derived from the adjective *quick*.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Some commonly used adjectives have irregular adverbial forms, such as *good*, which has the adverbial form *well*.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Modern English syntax is moderately analytic.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] It has developed features such as modal verbs and word order as resources for conveying meaning.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Auxiliary verbs mark constructions such as questions, negative polarity, the passive voice and progressive aspect.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] English has moved from the Germanic verb-second (V2) word order to being almost exclusively subject–verb–object (SVO).
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] The combination of SVO order and use of auxiliary verbs often creates clusters of two or more verbs at the centre of the sentence, such as "he had been hoping to try opening it".
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] In most sentences, English only marks grammatical relations through word order.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] The subject constituent precedes the verb and the object constituent follows it.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Indirect objects (IO) of ditransitive verbs can be placed either as the first object in a double object construction (S V IO O), such as "I gave *Jane* the book" or in a prepositional phrase, such as "I gave the book *to Jane*".
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] English sentences may be composed of one or more clauses, that may in turn be composed of one or more phrases (e.g. noun phrases, verb phrases, prepositional phrases).
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] A clause is built around a verb and includes its constituents, such as any noun or prepositional phrases.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Within a sentence, there is always at least one main clause (or matrix clause) whereas other clauses are subordinate to a main clause.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Subordinate clauses may function as arguments of the verb in the main clause.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] For example, in the phrase "I think (that) you are lying", the main clause is headed by the verb *think*, the subject is *I*, but the object of the phrase is the subordinate clause "(that) you are lying".
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] The subordinating conjunction *that* shows that the clause that follows is a subordinate clause, but it is often omitted.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Relative clauses can be introduced by the pronouns *who*, *whose*, *whom*, and *which* as well as by *that* (which can also be omitted).
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] In contrast to many other Germanic languages there are no major differences between word order in main and subordinate clauses.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] English auxiliary verbs are relied upon for many functions, including the expression of tense, aspect, and mood.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Auxiliary verbs form main clauses, and the main verbs function as heads of a subordinate clause of the auxiliary verb.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] For example, in the sentence "the dog did not find its bone", the clause "find its bone" is the complement of the negated verb *did not*.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Subject–auxiliary inversion is used in many constructions, including focus, negation, and interrogative constructions.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Negation is done with the adverb *not*, which precedes the main verb and follows an auxiliary verb.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] A contracted form of not -*n't* can be used as an enclitic attaching to auxiliary verbs and to the copula verb *to be*.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Just as with questions, many negative constructions require the negation to occur with *do*-support, thus in Modern English "I don't know him" is the correct answer to the question "Do you know him?", but not *"I know him not", although this construction may be found in older English.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Passive constructions also use auxiliary verbs.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] A passive construction rephrases an active construction in such a way that the object of the active phrase becomes the subject of the passive phrase, and the subject of the active phrase is either omitted or demoted to a role as an oblique argument introduced in a prepositional phrase.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] They are formed by using the past participle either with the auxiliary verb *to be* or *to get*, although not all varieties of English allow the use of passives with *get*.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] For example, putting the sentence "she sees him" into the passive becomes "he is seen (by her)", or "he gets seen (by her)".
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Both yes/no questions and *wh*-questions in English are mostly formed using subject–auxiliary inversion ("Am I going tomorrow?", "Where can we eat?"), which may require *do*-support ("Do you like her?", "Where did he go?").
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] In most cases, interrogative words (or wh*-words*) – which include *who*, *what*, *when*, *where*, *why*, and *how* – appear in a fronted position.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] For example, in the question "What did you see?", the word *what* appears as the first constituent despite being the grammatical object of the sentence.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] When the *wh*-word is the subject or forms part of the subject, no inversion occurs (e.g.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Prepositional phrases can also be fronted when they are the questions theme (e.g.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] "To whose house did you go last night?").
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] The personal interrogative pronoun *who* is the only interrogative pronoun to still show inflection for case, with the variant *whom* serving as the objective case form, although this form may be going out of use in many contexts.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] While English is a subject-prominent language, at the discourse level it tends to use a topic–comment structure, where the known information (topic) precedes the new information (comment).
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Because of the strict SVO syntax, the topic of a sentence generally has to be the grammatical subject of the sentence.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] In cases where the topic is not the grammatical subject of the sentence, it is often promoted to subject position through syntactic means.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] One way of doing this is through a passive construction, "the girl was stung by the bee".
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Another way is through a cleft sentence where the main clause is demoted to be a complement clause of a copula sentence with a dummy subject such as *it* or *there*, e.g.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] "it was the girl that the bee stung", "there was a girl who was stung by a bee".
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Dummy subjects are also used in constructions where there is no grammatical subject such as with impersonal verbs (e.g.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] "it is raining") or in existential clauses ("there are many cars on the street").
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Through the use of these complex sentence constructions with informationally vacuous subjects, English is able to maintain both a topic–comment sentence structure and a SVO syntax.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Focus constructions emphasise a particular piece of new or salient information within a sentence, generally through allocating the main sentence level stress on the focal constituent.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] For example, "the girl was stung by *a bee*" (emphasising it was a bee and not, for example, a wasp that stung her), or "*the girl* was stung by a bee" (contrasting with another possibility, for example that it was the boy).
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Topic and focus can also be established through syntactic dislocation, either preposing or postposing the item to be focused on relative to the main clause.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] For example, "That girl over there, she was stung by a bee", emphasises the girl by preposition, but a similar effect could be achieved by postposition, "she was stung by a bee, that girl over there", where reference to the girl is established as an afterthought.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Cohesion between sentences is achieved through the use of deictic pronouns as anaphora (e.g.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] "that is exactly what I mean" where *that* refers to some fact known to both interlocutors, or *then* used to locate the time of a narrated event relative to the time of a previously narrated event).
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Discourse markers such as *oh*, *so*, or *well*, also signal the progression of ideas between sentences and help to create cohesion.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Discourse markers are often the first constituents in sentences.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Discourse markers are also used for stance taking in which speakers position themselves in a specific attitude towards what is being said, for example, "no way is that true!" (the idiomatic marker "no way!" expressing disbelief), or "boy!
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] I'm hungry" (the marker *boy* expressing emphasis).
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] While discourse markers are particularly characteristic of informal and spoken registers of English, they are also used in written and formal registers.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] The English lexicon consists of around 170,000 words (or 220,000, if counting obsolete words), according to an estimate based on the 1989 edition of the *Oxford English Dictionary*.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Over one-half are nouns, one-quarter are adjectives, and one-seventh are verbs.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Another estimate – which includes scientific jargon, prefixed and suffixed words, loanwords of extremely limited use, technical acronyms, etc. – counts around 1 million total English words.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] English borrows vocabulary quickly from many languages and other sources.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Early studies of English vocabulary by lexicographers (scholars who study vocabulary and compile dictionaries) were impeded by a lack of comprehensive data on actual vocabulary in use from high-quality linguistic corpora (collections of actual written texts and spoken passages).
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Many statements published before the end of the 20th century about the growth of English vocabulary over time, the dates of first use of various words in English, and the sources of English vocabulary will have to be corrected as new computerised analyses of linguistic corpus data become available.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] English forms new words from existing words or roots in its vocabulary through a variety of processes.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] One of the most productive processes in English is conversion, using a word with a different grammatical role, for example using a noun as a verb or a verb as a noun.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Another productive word-formation process is nominal compounding, producing compound words such as *babysitter* or *ice cream* or *homesick*.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Formation of new words, called neologisms, based on Greek or Latin roots (for example *television* or *optometry*) is a highly productive process in modern European languages like English, so much so that it is often difficult to determine in which language a neologism originated.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] For this reason, American lexicographer Philip Gove attributed many such words to the "international scientific vocabulary" (ISV) when compiling *Webster's Third New International Dictionary* (1961).
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Another active word-formation process in English is that of acronyms, which result from pronouncing abbreviations of longer phrases as single words, e.g.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Throughout its history, English has been a particularly frequent borrower of loanwords from other languages.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] West Germanic words in use since the Anglo-Saxon period still comprise most of the language's core vocabulary, as well as most of its most frequently used words.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Many sentences can be constructed without loanwords, but not without core Anglo-Saxon vocabulary.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] English has formal and informal speech registers; informal registers, including child-directed speech, tend to be made up predominantly of Anglo-Saxon vocabulary, while Latinate vocabulary appears more frequently in legal, scientific, and academic writing.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Prolonged and intense contact with French has resulted in English having a very high proportion of Latinate words – with French loanwords borrowed during different stages of the language's history comprising 28 per cent of the English lexicon.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] In all periods of its history, English has also borrowed words from Latin directly, representing another 28 per cent of the lexicon.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] In turn, many of these words had originally entered Latin from Greek.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Greek and Latin stems remain highly productive sources for new literary, technical, and scientific vocabulary in English.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Loanwords from Old Norse primarily entered English between the 8th and 11th centuries, during the Norse colonisation of eastern and northern England, and typically displaced an Anglo-Saxon equivalent.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Many represent core vocabulary – including *give*, *get*, *sky*, *skirt*, *egg*, and *cake*.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] English has had a strong influence on the vocabulary of other languages.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] The influence of English stems from factors such as opinion leaders in other countries knowing the English language, the role of English as a world lingua franca, and the large number of books and films that are translated from English into other languages.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] This pervasive use of English leads to the conclusion in many places that English is an especially suitable language for expressing new ideas or describing new technologies.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Among the varieties of English, it is especially American English that influences other languages.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Some languages, such as Chinese, write words borrowed from English mostly as calques, while others, such as Japanese, readily take in English loanwords written in a sound‑indicating script.
[src:apple-wine/english-language-p02] Dubbed films and television programmes are a particularly fruitful source of English influence on languages in Europe.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] German is one of the major languages of the world, with nearly 100 million native speakers and over 130 million total speakers as of 2024.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] It is the most spoken native language within the European Union.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] German is the second-most widely spoken Germanic language, after English, both as a first and as a second language.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Overall, German is the fourth most commonly learned second language globally.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The language has been influential in the fields of philosophy, theology, science, and technology.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] It is the second most commonly used language in science and the third most widely used language on websites.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The German-speaking countries are ranked fifth in terms of annual publication of new books, with one-tenth of all books (including e-books) in the world being published in German.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] German is most closely related to other West Germanic languages, namely Afrikaans, Dutch, English, the Frisian languages, and Scots.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] It also contains close similarities in vocabulary to some languages in the North Germanic group, such as Danish, Norwegian, and Swedish.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Modern German gradually developed from Old High German, which in turn developed from Proto-Germanic during the Early Middle Ages.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] German is an inflected language, with four cases for nouns, pronouns, and adjectives (nominative, accusative, genitive, dative); three genders (masculine, feminine, neuter) and two numbers (singular, plural).
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The majority of its vocabulary is derived from the ancient Germanic branch of the Indo-European language family, while a smaller share is partly derived from Latin and Greek, along with fewer words borrowed from French and Modern English.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] English, however, is the main source of more recent loanwords.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] German is a pluricentric language; the three standardised variants are German, Austrian, and Swiss Standard German.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Standard German is sometimes called *High German*, which refers to its regional origin.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] German is also notable for its broad spectrum of dialects, with many varieties existing in Europe and other parts of the world.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Some of these non-standard varieties have become recognised and protected by regional or national governments.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Since 2004, heads of state of the German-speaking countries have met every year, and the Council for German Orthography has been the main international body regulating German orthography.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] German is an Indo-European language that belongs to the West Germanic group of the Germanic languages.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The Germanic languages are traditionally subdivided into three branches: North Germanic, East Germanic, and West Germanic.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The first of these branches survives in modern Danish, Swedish, Norwegian, Faroese, and Icelandic, all of which are descended from Old Norse.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The East Germanic languages are now extinct, and Gothic is the only language in this branch which survives in written texts.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The West Germanic languages, however, have undergone extensive dialectal subdivision and are now represented in modern languages such as English, German, Dutch, Yiddish, Afrikaans, and others.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The various regional dialects spoken south of these lines are grouped as High German dialects, while those spoken to the north comprise the Low German and Low Franconian dialects.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] As members of the West Germanic language family, High German, Low German, and Low Franconian have been proposed to be further distinguished historically as Irminonic, Ingvaeonic, and Istvaeonic, respectively.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] This classification indicates their historical descent from dialects spoken by the Irminones (also known as the Elbe group), Ingvaeones (or North Sea Germanic group), and Istvaeones (or Weser–Rhine group).
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Standard German is based on a combination of Thuringian-Upper Saxon and Upper Franconian dialects, which are Central German and Upper German dialects belonging to the High German dialect group.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] German is therefore closely related to the other languages based on High German dialects, such as Luxembourgish (based on Central Franconian dialects) and Yiddish.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] After these High German dialects, standard German is less closely related to languages based on Low Franconian dialects (e.g., Dutch and Afrikaans), Low German or Low Saxon dialects (spoken in northern Germany and southern Denmark), neither of which underwent the High German consonant shift.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] As has been noted, the former of these dialect types is Istvaeonic and the latter Ingvaeonic, whereas the High German dialects are all Irminonic; the differences between these languages and standard German are therefore considerable.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Also related to German are the Frisian languages—North Frisian (spoken in Nordfriesland), Saterland Frisian (spoken in Saterland), and West Frisian (spoken in Friesland)—as well as the Anglic languages of English and Scots.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] These Anglo-Frisian dialects did not take part in the High German consonant shift, and the Anglic languages also adopted much vocabulary from both Old Norse and the Norman language.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The history of the German language begins with the High German consonant shift during the Migration Period, which separated Old High German dialects from Old Saxon.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] This sound shift involved a drastic change in the pronunciation of both voiced and voiceless stop consonants (*b*, *d*, *g*, and *p*, *t*, *k*, respectively).
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The primary effects of the shift were the following below.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] While there is written evidence of the Old High German language in several Elder Futhark inscriptions from as early as the sixth century AD (such as the Pforzen buckle), the Old High German period is generally seen as beginning with the *Abrogans* (written c.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] 765–775), a Latin-German glossary supplying over 3,000 Old High German words with their Latin equivalents.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] After the *Abrogans*, the first coherent works written in Old High German appear in the ninth century, chief among them being the *Muspilli*, Merseburg charms, and **Hildebrandslied**, and other religious texts (the *Georgslied*, *Ludwigslied*, *Evangelienbuch*, and translated hymns and prayers).
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The *Muspilli* is a Christian poem written in a Bavarian dialect offering an account of the soul after the Last Judgment, and the Merseburg charms are transcriptions of spells and charms from the pagan Germanic tradition.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Of particular interest to scholars, however, has been the **Hildebrandslied**, a secular epic poem telling the tale of an estranged father and son unknowingly meeting each other in battle.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Linguistically, this text is highly interesting due to the mixed use of Old Saxon and Old High German dialects in its composition.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The written works of this period stem mainly from the Alamanni, Bavarian, and Thuringian groups, all belonging to the Elbe Germanic group (Irminones), which had settled in what is now southern-central Germany and Austria between the second and sixth centuries, during the great migration.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] In general, the surviving texts of Old High German (OHG) show a wide range of dialectal diversity with very little written uniformity.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The early written tradition of OHG survived mostly through monasteries and scriptoria as local translations of Latin originals; as a result, the surviving texts are written in highly disparate regional dialects and exhibit significant Latin influence, particularly in vocabulary.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] At this point monasteries, where most written works were produced, were dominated by Latin, and German saw only occasional use in official and ecclesiastical writing.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] While there is no complete agreement over the dates of the Middle High German (MHG) period, it is generally seen as lasting from 1050 to 1350.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] This was a period of significant expansion of the geographical territory occupied by Germanic tribes, and consequently of the number of German speakers.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Whereas during the Old High German period the Germanic tribes extended only as far east as the Elbe and Saale rivers, the MHG period saw a number of these tribes expanding beyond this eastern boundary into Slavic territory (known as the **Ostsiedlung**).
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] With the increasing wealth and geographic spread of the Germanic groups came greater use of German in the courts of nobles as the standard language of official proceedings and literature.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] A clear example of this is the **mittelhochdeutsche Dichtersprache** employed in the Hohenstaufen court in Swabia as a standardised supra-dialectal written language.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] While these efforts were still regionally bound, German began to be used in place of Latin for certain official purposes, leading to a greater need for regularity in written conventions.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] A great wealth of texts survives from the MHG period.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Significantly, these texts include a number of impressive secular works, such as the *Nibelungenlied*, an epic poem telling the story of the dragon-slayer Siegfried (c. thirteenth century), and the *Iwein*, an Arthurian verse poem by Hartmann von Aue (c.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] 1203), lyric poems, and courtly romances such as *Parzival* and *Tristan*.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Also noteworthy is the **Sachsenspiegel**, the first book of laws written in Middle *Low* German (c.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The abundance and especially the secular character of the literature of the MHG period demonstrate the beginnings of a standardised written form of German, as well as the desire of poets and authors to be understood by individuals on supra-dialectal terms.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The Middle High German period is generally seen as ending when the 1346–53 Black Death decimated Europe's population.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Modern High German begins with the Early New High German (ENHG) period, which Wilhelm Scherer dates 1350–1650, terminating with the end of the Thirty Years' War.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] This period saw the further displacement of Latin by German as the primary language of courtly proceedings and, increasingly, of literature in the German states.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] While these states were still part of the Holy Roman Empire, and far from any form of unification, the desire for a cohesive written language that would be understandable across the many German-speaking principalities and kingdoms was stronger than ever.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] As a spoken language German remained highly fractured throughout this period, with a vast number of often mutually incomprehensible regional dialects being spoken throughout the German states; the invention of the printing press c.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] 1440 and the publication of Luther's vernacular translation of the Bible in 1534, however, had an immense effect on standardising German as a supra-dialectal written language.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The ENHG period saw the rise of several important cross-regional forms of chancery German, one being **gemeine tiutsch**, used in the court of the Holy Roman Emperor Maximilian I, and the other being **Meißner Deutsch**, used in the Electorate of Saxony in the Duchy of Saxe-Wittenberg.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Alongside these courtly written standards, the invention of the printing press led to the development of a number of printers' languages (**Druckersprachen**) aimed at making printed material readable and understandable across as many diverse dialects of German as possible.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The greater ease of production and increased availability of written texts brought about increased standardisation in the written form of German.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] One of the central events in the development of ENHG was the publication of Luther's translation of the Bible into High German (the New Testament was published in 1522; the Old Testament was published in parts and completed in 1534).
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Luther based his translation primarily on the **Meißner Deutsch** of Saxony, spending much time among the population of Saxony researching the dialect so as to make the work as natural and accessible to German speakers as possible.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Copies of Luther's Bible featured a long list of glosses for each region, translating words which were unknown in the region into the regional dialect.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Luther's translation of the Bible into High German was also decisive for the German language and its evolution from Early New High German to modern Standard German.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The publication of Luther's Bible was a decisive moment in the spread of literacy in early modern Germany, and promoted the development of non-local forms of language and exposed all speakers to forms of German from outside their own area.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] With Luther's rendering of the Bible in the vernacular, German asserted itself against the dominance of Latin as a legitimate language for courtly, literary, and now ecclesiastical subject-matter.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] His Bible was ubiquitous in the German states: nearly every household possessed a copy.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Nevertheless, even with the influence of Luther's Bible as an unofficial written standard, a widely accepted standard for written German did not appear until the middle of the eighteenth century.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] German was the language of commerce and government in the Habsburg Empire, which encompassed a large area of Central and Eastern Europe.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Until the mid-nineteenth century, it was essentially the language of townspeople throughout most of the Empire.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Its use indicated that the speaker was a merchant or someone from an urban area, regardless of nationality.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Prague (German: *Prag*) and Budapest (Buda, German: *Ofen*), to name two examples, were gradually Germanised in the years after their incorporation into the Habsburg domain.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] However, Prague had a large German-speaking population since the Middle Ages, as had Pressburg (Pozsony, now Bratislava), which was settled by Germans in the 10th century.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Significant portions of Bohemia and Moravia, now part of the Czech Republic, had become German-speaking during Ostsiedlung.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] During the Habsburg time, Budapest and cities like Zagreb (German: *Agram*) or Ljubljana (German: *Laibach*), contained significant German minorities.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] In 1901, the Second Orthographic Conference ended with a (nearly) complete standardisation of the Standard German language in its written form, and the Duden Handbook was declared its standard definition.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Punctuation and compound spelling (joined or isolated compounds) were not standardised in the process.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] 'German stage language') by Theodor Siebs had established conventions for German pronunciation in theatres, three years earlier; however, this was an artificial standard that did not correspond to any traditional spoken dialect.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] In Northern Germany, High German was a foreign language to most inhabitants, whose native dialects were subsets of Low German.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] It was usually encountered only in writing or formal speech; in fact, most of High German was a written language, not identical to any spoken dialect, throughout the German-speaking area until well into the 19th century.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] However, wider standardisation of pronunciation was established on the basis of public speaking in theatres and the media during the 20th century and documented in pronouncing dictionaries.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Official revisions of some of the rules from 1901 were not issued until the controversial German orthography reform of 1996 was made the official standard by governments of all German-speaking countries.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Media and written works are now almost all produced in Standard German which is understood in all areas where German is spoken.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] As a result of the German diaspora, as well as the popularity of German taught as a foreign language, the geographical distribution of German speakers (or "Germanophones") spans all inhabited continents.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] With the inclusion or exclusion of certain varieties, it is estimated that approximately 90–95 million people speak German as a first language, 10–25 million speak it as a second language, and 75–100 million as a foreign language.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] This would imply the existence of approximately 175–220 million German speakers worldwide.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] German sociolinguist Ulrich Ammon estimated a number of 289 million German foreign language speakers without clarifying the criteria by which he classified a speaker.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The area in central Europe where the majority of the population speaks German as a first language and has German as a (co-)official language is called the "German *Sprachraum*".
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] As a result of implementation of the Oder–Neisse line and ensuing expulsion and ethnic cleansing in post-war Poland, the German Sprachraum significantly shrank, as well as by dissolution of the large German-speaking areas in Bohemia and Moravia.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Former German-speaking exclaves of East Prussia, the Free City of Danzig and the Memelland ceased to exist, while Francization in Alsace and Lorraine removed use of German in these areas.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Although expulsions and (forced) assimilation after the two World wars greatly diminished them, minority communities of mostly bilingual German native speakers exist in areas both adjacent to and detached from the Sprachraum.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] In France, the High German varieties of Alsatian and Moselle Franconian are identified as "regional languages", but the European Charter for Regional or Minority Languages of 1998 has not yet been ratified by the government.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] In the Baltic states of Estonia, Latvia, and Lithuania, there are still around 8,000 members of the German minority (Baltic Germans, East Prussians, and Russian Germans) who speak Standard German and, to some extent, Low German.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] For Estonia, the number is estimated quite precisely at under 2,000 (in 2000: 1,870), for Latvia at just over 3,000 (in 2004: 3,311), and also for Lithuania at just over 3,000.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] In 2010, 394,000 Germans lived in Russia, some of whom spoke German.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] After the collapse of the Soviet Union, many Russian Germans immigrated to Germany.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Namibia also was a colony of the German Empire, from 1884 to 1915.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] About 30,000 people still speak German as a native tongue today, mostly descendants of German colonial settlers.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The period of German colonialism in Namibia also led to the evolution of a Standard German-based pidgin language called "Namibian Black German", which became a second language for parts of the indigenous population.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Although it is nearly extinct today, some older Namibians still have some knowledge of it.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] German remained a *de facto* official language of Namibia after the end of German colonial rule alongside English and Afrikaans, and had *de jure* co-official status from 1984 until its independence from South Africa in 1990.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] However, the Namibian government perceived Afrikaans and German as symbols of apartheid and colonialism, and decided English would be the sole official language upon independence, stating that it was a "neutral" language as there were virtually no English native speakers in Namibia at that time.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] German, Afrikaans, and several indigenous languages thus became "national languages" by law, identifying them as elements of the cultural heritage of the nation and ensuring that the state acknowledged and supported their presence in the country.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Today, Namibia is considered to be the only German-speaking country outside of the *Sprachraum* in Europe.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The *Allgemeine Zeitung* is one of the three biggest newspapers in Namibia and the only German-language daily in Africa.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] An estimated 12,000 people speak German or a German variety as a first language in South Africa, mostly originating from different waves of immigration during the 19th and 20th centuries.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] One of the largest communities consists of the speakers of "Nataler Deutsch", a variety of Low German concentrated in and around Wartburg.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The South African constitution identifies German as a "commonly used" language and the Pan South African Language Board is obligated to promote and ensure respect for it.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Cameroon was also a colony of the German Empire from the same period (1884 to 1916).
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] However, German was replaced by French and English, the languages of the two successor colonial powers, after its loss in World War I.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Nevertheless, since the 21st century, German has become a popular foreign language among pupils and students, with 300,000 people learning or speaking German in Cameroon in 2010 and over 230,000 in 2020.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Today Cameroon is one of the African countries outside Namibia with the highest number of people learning German.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] In the United States, German is the fifth most spoken language in terms of native and second language speakers after English, Spanish, French, and Chinese (with figures for Cantonese and Mandarin combined), with over 1 million total speakers.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] In the states of North Dakota and South Dakota, German is the most common language spoken at home after English.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] As a legacy of significant German immigration to the country, German geographical names can be found throughout the Midwest region, such as New Ulm and Bismarck (North Dakota's state capital), plus many other regions.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] A number of German varieties have developed in the country and are still spoken today, such as Pennsylvania Dutch and Texas German.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] In Brazil, the largest concentrations of German speakers are in the states of Rio Grande do Sul (where Riograndenser Hunsrückisch developed), Santa Catarina, and Espírito Santo.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Standard German is a recognised language in the Brazilian municipalities of Pomerode and São João do Oeste.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] In Chile, during the 19th and 20th centuries, there was a massive immigration of Germans, Swiss and Austrians.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Because of that, two dialects of German emerged, Lagunen-Deutsch and Chiloten-Deutsch.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Immigrants even founded prosperous cities and towns.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The impact of nineteenth century German immigration to southern Chile was such that Valdivia was for a while a Spanish-German bilingual city with "German signboards and placards alongside the Spanish".
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Currently, German and its dialects are spoken in many cities, towns and rural areas of southern Chile, such as Valdivia, Osorno, Puerto Montt, Puerto Varas, Frutillar, Nueva Braunau, Castro, Ancud, among many others.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Small concentrations of German-speakers and their descendants are also found in Argentina, Chile, Paraguay, Venezuela, and Bolivia.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] In Australia, the state of South Australia experienced a pronounced wave of Prussian immigration in the 1840s (particularly from Silesia region).
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] With the prolonged isolation from other German speakers and contact with Australian English, a unique dialect known as Barossa German developed, spoken predominantly in the Barossa Valley near Adelaide.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Usage of German sharply declined with the advent of World War I, due to the prevailing anti-German sentiment in the population and related government action.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] It continued to be used as a first language into the 20th century, but its use is now limited to a few older speakers.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] As of the 2013 census, 36,642 people in New Zealand spoke German, mostly descendants of a small wave of 19th century German immigrants, making it the third most spoken European language after English and French and overall the ninth most spoken language.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] A German creole named *Unserdeutsch* was historically spoken in the former German colony of German New Guinea, modern day Papua New Guinea.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] It is at a high risk of extinction, with only about 100 speakers remaining, and a topic of interest among linguists seeking to revive interest in the language.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Like English, French, and Spanish, German has become a standard foreign language throughout the world, especially in the Western World.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] German ranks second on par with French among the best known foreign languages in the European Union (EU) after English, as well as in Russia, and Turkey.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] In terms of student numbers across all levels of education, German ranks third in the EU (after English and French) and in the United States (after Spanish and French).
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] In British schools, where learning a foreign language is not mandatory, a dramatic decline in entries for German A-Level has been observed.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] In 2020, approximately 15.4 million people were enrolled in learning German across all levels of education worldwide.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] This number has decreased from a peak of 20.1 million in 2000.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Within the EU, not counting countries where it is an official language, German as a foreign language is most popular in Eastern and Northern Europe, namely the Czech Republic, Croatia, Denmark, Greece, Hungary, the Netherlands, Norway, Poland, Slovakia, Slovenia, Bosnia and Herzegovina, and Serbia.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] German was once, and to some extent still is, a lingua franca in those parts of Europe.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] A visible sign of the geographical extension of the German language is the German-language media outside the German-speaking countries.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] German is the second most commonly used scientific language as well as the third most widely used language on websites after English and Spanish.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Deutsche Welle (German pronunciation: [ˈdɔʏtʃə ˈvɛlə]; "*German Wave*" in German), or **DW**, is Germany's public international broadcaster.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The service is available in 30 languages.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] DW's satellite television service consists of channels in German, English, Spanish, and Arabic.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The basis of Standard German developed with the Luther Bible and the chancery language spoken by the Saxon court, part of the regional High German group.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] However, there are places where the traditional regional dialects have been replaced by new vernaculars based on Standard German, which is the case in large stretches of Northern Germany but also in major cities in other parts of the country.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] However, the remains that the colloquial Standard German differs from the formal written language, especially in grammar and syntax, in which it has been influenced by dialectal speech.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Standard German differs regionally among German-speaking countries in vocabulary and some instances of pronunciation and even grammar and orthography.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] This variation must not be confused with the variation of local dialects.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Even though the national varieties of Standard German are only somewhat influenced by the local dialects, they are very distinct.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] German is thus considered a pluricentric language, with currently three national standard varieties of German: German Standard German, Austrian Standard German and Swiss Standard German.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] In comparison to other European languages (e.g., Portuguese, English), the multi-standard character of German is still not widely acknowledged.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] However, 90% of Austrian secondary school teachers of German consider German as having "more than one" standard variety.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] In this context, some scholars speak of a One Standard German Axiom that has been maintained as a core assumption of German dialectology.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] In most regions, the speakers use a continuum, e.g., "Umgangssprache" (colloquial standards) from more dialectal varieties to more standard varieties depending on the circumstances.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] In German linguistics, German dialects are distinguished from varieties of Standard German.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The *varieties of Standard German* refer to the different local varieties of the pluricentric German.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] They differ mainly in lexicon and phonology, but also smaller grammatical differences.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] In certain regions, they have replaced the traditional German dialects, especially in Northern Germany.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] In the German-speaking parts of Switzerland, mixtures of dialect and standard are very seldom used, and the use of Standard German is largely restricted to the written language.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] About 11% of Swiss residents speak Standard German at home, but this is mainly due to German immigrants.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] This situation has been called a *medial diglossia*.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Swiss Standard German is used in the Swiss education system, while Austrian German is officially used in the Austrian education system.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The German dialects are the traditional local varieties of the language; many of them are not mutually intelligible with standard German, and they have great differences in lexicon, phonology, and syntax.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] If a narrow definition of language based on mutual intelligibility is used, many German dialects are considered to be separate languages (for instance by ISO 639-3).
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] However, such a point of view is unusual in German linguistics.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The German dialect continuum is traditionally divided most broadly into High German and Low German, also called Low Saxon.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] However, historically, High German dialects and Low Saxon/Low German dialects do not belong to the same language.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Nevertheless, in today's Germany, Low Saxon/Low German is often perceived as a dialectal variation of Standard German on a functional level even by many native speakers.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The variation among the German dialects is considerable, with often only neighbouring dialects being mutually intelligible.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Some dialects are not intelligible to people who know only Standard German.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] However, all German dialects belong to the dialect continuum of High German and Low Saxon.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Middle Low German was the lingua franca of the Hanseatic League.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] It was the predominant language in Northern Germany until the 16th century.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] In 1534, the Luther Bible was published.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] It aimed to be understandable to a broad audience and was based mainly on Central and Upper German varieties.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The Early New High German language gained more prestige than Low German and became the language of science and literature.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Around the same time, the Hanseatic League, a confederation of northern ports, lost its importance as new trade routes to Asia and the Americas were established, and the most powerful German states of that period were located in Middle and Southern Germany.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The 18th and 19th centuries were marked by mass education in Standard German in schools.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Gradually, Low German came to be politically viewed as a mere dialect spoken by the uneducated.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The proportion of the population who can understand and speak it has decreased continuously since World War II.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The Low Franconian dialects fall within a linguistic category used to classify a number of historical and contemporary West Germanic varieties most closely related to, and including, the Dutch language.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Consequently, the vast majority of the Low Franconian dialects are spoken outside of the German language area.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Low Franconian dialects are spoken in the Netherlands, Belgium, South Africa, Namibia, and Suriname, and along the Lower Rhine in Germany, in North Rhine-Westphalia.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The region in Germany encompasses parts of the Rhine-Ruhr metropolitan region.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The Low Franconian dialects have three different standard varieties: In the Netherlands, Belgium and Suriname, it is Dutch, which is itself a Low Franconian language.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] In South Africa, it is Afrikaans, which is also categorised as Low Franconian.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] During the Middle Ages and Early Modern Period, the Low Franconian dialects now spoken in Germany, used Middle Dutch or Early Modern Dutch as their literary language and Dachsprache.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Following a 19th-century change in Prussian language policy, use of Dutch as an official and public language was forbidden; resulting in Standard German taking its place as the region's official language.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] As a result, these dialects are now considered German dialects from a socio-linguistic point of view.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The Low Franconian dialects in Germany are divided by the Uerdingen line (north of which the word for "I" is pronounced as "ik" and south of which as "ich") into northern and southern Low Franconian.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The northern variants comprise Kleverlandish, which is most similar to Standard Dutch.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The other ones are transitional between Low Franconian and Ripuarian, but closer to Low Franconian.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The High German dialects consist of the Central German, High Franconian and Upper German dialects.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The High Franconian dialects are transitional dialects between Central and Upper German.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The High German varieties spoken by the Ashkenazi Jews have several unique features and are considered as a separate language, Yiddish, written with the Hebrew alphabet.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The Central German dialects are spoken in Central Germany, from Aachen in the west to Görlitz in the east.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Modern Standard German is mostly based on Central German dialects.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The West Central German dialects are the Central Franconian dialects (Ripuarian and Moselle Franconian) and the Rhenish Franconian dialects (Hessian and Palatine).
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Luxembourgish as well as Transylvanian Saxon and Banat Swabian are based on Moselle Franconian dialects.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] They consist of the East and South Franconian dialects.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The East Franconian dialects are spoken in the region of Franconia.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] Franconia consists of the Bavarian districts of Upper, Middle, and Lower Franconia, the region of South Thuringia (those parts of Thuringia south of the Thuringian Forest), and the eastern parts of the region of Heilbronn-Franken (Tauber Franconia and Hohenlohe) in northeastern Baden-Württemberg.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] East Franconian is also spoken in most parts of Saxon Vogtland (in the Vogtland District around Plauen, Reichenbach im Vogtland, Auerbach/Vogtl., Oelsnitz/Vogtl. and Klingenthal).
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] East Franconian is colloquially referred to as "Fränkisch" (Franconian) in Franconia (including Bavarian Vogtland), and as "Vogtländisch" (Vogtlandian) in Saxon Vogtland.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] South Franconian is spoken in northern Baden-Württemberg and in the northeasternmost tip of Alsace (around Wissembourg) in France.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] In Baden-Württemberg, they are considered dialects of German, and in Alsace a South Franconian variant of Alsatian.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The Upper German dialects are the Alemannic and Swabian dialects in the west and the Austro-Bavarian dialects in the east.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] In Germany, the Alemannic dialects are often referred to as Swabian in Bavarian Swabia and in the historical region of Württemberg, and as Badian in the historical region of Baden.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The southernmost German-speaking municipality is in the Alemannic region: Zermatt in the Canton of Valais, Switzerland, as is the capital of Liechtenstein: Vaduz.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The Austro-Bavarian dialects are spoken in Austria (Vienna, Lower and Upper Austria, Styria, Carinthia, Salzburg, Burgenland, and in most parts of Tyrol), southern and eastern Bavaria (Upper and Lower Bavaria as well as Upper Palatinate), and South Tyrol.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] There is also one single Austro-Bavarian village in Switzerland: Samnaun in the Canton of the Grisons.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p01] The northernmost Austro-Bavarian village is Breitenfeld (municipality of Markneukirchen, Saxony), the southernmost village is Salorno sulla Strada del Vino (German: Salurn an der Weinstraße), South Tyrol.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Written texts in German are easily recognisable as such by distinguishing features such as umlauts and certain orthographical features, such as the capitalisation of all nouns, and the frequent occurrence of long compounds.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Because legibility and convenience set certain boundaries, compounds consisting of more than three or four nouns are almost exclusively found in humorous contexts.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] In German orthography, nouns are capitalised, which makes it easier for readers to determine the function of a word within a sentence.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Before the German orthography reform of 1996, *ß* replaced *ss* after long vowels and diphthongs and before consonants, word-, or partial-word endings.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] In reformed spelling, *ß* replaces *ss* only after long vowels and diphthongs.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Since there is no traditional capital form of *ß*, it was replaced by *SS* (or *SZ*) when capitalisation was required.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] For example, *Maßband* (tape measure) became *MASSBAND* in capitals.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] An exception was the use of ß in legal documents and forms when capitalising names.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] To avoid confusion with similar names, lower case *ß* was sometimes maintained (thus "*KREßLEIN*" instead of "*KRESSLEIN*").
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Capital ß (ẞ) was ultimately adopted into German orthography in 2017, ending a long orthographic debate (thus "*KREẞLEIN* and *KRESSLEIN*").
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Umlaut vowels (ä, ö, ü) are commonly transcribed with ae, oe, and ue if the umlauts are not available on the keyboard or other medium used.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] In the same manner, ß can be transcribed as ss.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Some operating systems use key sequences to extend the set of possible characters to include, amongst other things, umlauts; in Microsoft Windows this is done using Alt codes.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] German readers understand these transcriptions (although they appear unusual), but they are avoided if the regular umlauts are available, because they are a makeshift and not proper spelling.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] There is no general agreement on where letters with umlauts occur in the sorting sequence.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Telephone directories treat them by replacing them with the base vowel followed by an e.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Some dictionaries sort each umlauted vowel as a separate letter after the base vowel, but more commonly words with umlauts are ordered immediately after the same word without umlauts.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] As an example in a telephone book *Ärzte* occurs after *Adressenverlage* but before *Anlagenbauer* (because Ä is replaced by Ae).
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] In a dictionary *Ärzte* comes after *Arzt*, but in some dictionaries *Ärzte* and all other words starting with *Ä* may occur after all words starting with *A*.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] In some older dictionaries or indexes, initial *Sch* and *St* are treated as separate letters and are listed as separate entries after *S*, but they are usually treated as S+C+H and S+T.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Written German also typically uses an alternative opening inverted comma (quotation mark) as in *„Guten Morgen!“*.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Until the early 20th century, German was printed in blackletter typefaces (in Fraktur, and in Schwabacher), and written in corresponding handwriting (for example Kurrent and Sütterlin).
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] These variants of the Latin alphabet are very different from the serif or sans-serif Antiqua typefaces used today, and the handwritten forms in particular are difficult for the untrained to read.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] The printed forms, however, were claimed by some to be more readable when used for Germanic languages.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] The Nazis initially promoted Fraktur and Schwabacher because they were considered Aryan, but abolished them in 1941, claiming the letters were Jewish.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] It is also believed this script was banned, as the German government understood Fraktur would inhibit communication in the territories occupied during World War II.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] The Fraktur script however remains present in everyday life in pub signs, beer brands and other forms of advertisement, where it is used to convey a certain rusticality and antiquity.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] A proper use of the long s (*langes s*), ſ, is essential for writing German text in Fraktur typefaces.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Many Antiqua typefaces also include the long s.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] A specific set of rules applies for the use of long s in German text, but nowadays it is rarely used in Antiqua typesetting.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Any lower case "s" at the beginning of a syllable would be a long s, as opposed to a terminal s or short s (the more common variation of the letter s), which marks the end of a syllable; for example, in differentiating between the words *Wachſtube* (guard-house) and *Wachstube* (tube of polish/wax).
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] One can easily decide which "s" to use by appropriate hyphenation, (*Wach-ſtube* vs.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] German is a fusional language with a moderate degree of inflection, with three grammatical genders; as such, there can be a large number of words derived from the same root.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] This degree of inflection is considerably less than in Old High German and other old Indo-European languages such as Latin, Ancient Greek, and Sanskrit, and it is also somewhat less than, for instance, Old English, modern Icelandic, or Russian.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] The three genders have collapsed in the plural.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] With four cases and three genders plus plural, there are 16 permutations of case and gender/number of the article (not the nouns), but there are only six forms of the definite article, which together cover all 16 permutations.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] In nouns, inflection for case is required in the singular for strong masculine and neuter nouns only in the genitive and in the dative (only in fixed or archaic expressions), and even this is losing ground to substitutes in informal speech.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Weak masculine nouns share a common case ending for genitive, dative, and accusative in the singular.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Feminine nouns are not declined in the singular.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] The plural has an inflection for the dative.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] In total, seven inflectional endings (not counting plural markers) exist in German: *-s, -es, -n, -ns, -en, -ens, -e*.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Like the other Germanic languages, German forms noun compounds in which the first noun modifies the category given by the second: *Hundehütte* ("dog hut"; specifically: "dog kennel").
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Unlike English, whose newer compounds or combinations of longer nouns are often written "open" with separating spaces, German (like some other Germanic languages) nearly always uses the "closed" form without spaces, for example: *Baumhaus* ("tree house").
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Like English, German allows arbitrarily long compounds in theory (see also English compounds).
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] However, examples like this are perceived by native speakers as excessively bureaucratic, stylistically awkward, or even satirical.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] On the other hand, even this compound could be expanded by any native speaker.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] The meaning of basic verbs can be expanded and sometimes radically changed through the use of a number of prefixes.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Some prefixes have a specific meaning; the prefix ***zer-*** refers to destruction, as in ***zer**reißen* (to tear apart), ***zer**brechen* (to break apart), ***zer**schneiden* (to cut apart).
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Other examples include the following: *haften* (to stick), ***ver**haften* (to detain); *kaufen* (to buy), ***ver**kaufen* (to sell); *hören* (to hear), ***auf**hören* (to cease); *fahren* (to drive), ***er**fahren* (to experience).
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Many German verbs have a separable prefix, often with an adverbial function.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] In finite verb forms, it is split off and moved to the end of the clause and is hence considered by some to be a "resultative particle".
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] For example, *mitgehen*, meaning "to go along", would be split, giving *Gehen Sie mit?* (Literal: "Go you with?"; Idiomatic: "Are you going along?").
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] He "came" on Friday evening, after a hard day at work and the usual annoyances that had time and again been troubling him for years now at his workplace, with questionable joy, to a meal which, as he hoped, his wife had already put on the table, finally home "to".
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] German word order is generally with the V2 word order restriction and also with the SOV word order restriction for subordinate as well as for main clauses including an auxiliary verb.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] As to subordinate clauses, all verb forms occur at the very end.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] For yes–no questions, exclamations, and wishes, the finite verb usually has the first position.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] German requires a verbal element (main verb, modal verb or auxiliary verb as finite verb) to appear second in the sentence.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] The verb is preceded by the topic of the sentence or an adverbial of flexible length.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] The element in focus appears at the end of the sentence.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] While the subject typically precedes the object, the position of a noun in a German sentence has no bearing on its being a subject, an object or another argument.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] In a declarative sentence in English, if the subject does not occur before the predicate, the sentence could well be misunderstood.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Der Direktor betrat gestern um 10 Uhr mit einem Schirm in der Hand sein Büro.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] The manager entered yesterday at 10 o'clock with an umbrella in the hand his office.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Der Direktor betrat sein Büro gestern um 10 Uhr mit einem Schirm in der Hand.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] The manager entered his office yesterday at 10 o'clock with an umbrella in the hand.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] This variant accentuates the time specification and that he carried an umbrella.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Sein Büro betrat der Direktor gestern um 10 Uhr mit einem Schirm in der Hand.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] His office entered the manager yesterday at 10 o'clock with an umbrella in the hand.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] (his office) is thus highlighted; it could be the topic of the next sentence.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Gestern betrat der Direktor um 10 Uhr mit einem Schirm in der Hand sein Büro.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Yesterday entered the manager at 10 o'clock with an umbrella in the hand his office.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Yesterday at 10 o'clock entered the manager with an umbrella in the hand his office.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Yesterday at 10 o'clock entered the manager his office with an umbrella in the hand.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Both the time specification and the fact he carried an umbrella are accentuated.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Der Direktor betrat mit einem Schirm in der Hand gestern um 10 Uhr sein Büro.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] The manager entered with an umbrella in the hand yesterday at 10 o'clock his office.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Der Direktor betrat gestern um 10 Uhr sein Büro mit einem Schirm in der Hand.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] The manager entered yesterday at 10 o'clock his office with an umbrella in the hand.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] The flexible word order also allows one to use language "tools" (such as poetic metre and figures of speech) more freely.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] When an auxiliary verb is present in the main clause, it appears in second position, and the main verb appears at the end.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] This occurs notably in the creation of the perfect tense.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Der alte Mann hat mir heute das Buch gegeben.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Das Buch hat der alte Mann mir heute gegeben.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Heute hat der alte Mann mir das Buch gegeben.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] The main verb may appear in first position to put stress on the action itself.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] The auxiliary verb is still in second position.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Gegeben hat mir der alte Mann das Buch heute.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] .) The bare fact that the book has been given is emphasised, as well as 'today'.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Sentences using modal verbs as finite verbs place the infinitive at the end.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] For example, the English sentence "Should he go home?" would be rearranged in German to say "Should he (to) home go?" (*Soll er nach Hause gehen?*).
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Thus, in sentences with several subordinate or relative clauses, the infinitives are clustered at the end.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] German subordinate clauses have all verbs clustered at the end, with the finite verb normally in the final position of the cluster.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Given that auxiliaries encode future, passive, modality, and the perfect, very long chains of verbs at the end of the sentence can occur.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] In these constructions, the past participle formed with *ge-* is often replaced by the infinitive.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] One suspects that the deserter probably shot become be should.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] The order at the end of such strings is subject to variation, but the second one in the last example is unusual.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Most German vocabulary is derived from the Germanic branch of the Indo-European language family.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] However, there is a significant number of loanwords from other languages, in particular Latin, Greek, Italian, French, and most recently English.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] In the early 19th century, Joachim Heinrich Campe estimated that one fifth of the total German vocabulary was of French or Latin origin.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Latin words were already imported into the predecessor of the German language during the Roman Empire and underwent all the characteristic phonetic changes in German.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Their origin is thus no longer recognisable for most speakers (e.g., *Pforte*, *Tafel*, *Mauer*, *Käse*, *Köln* from Latin *porta*, *tabula*, *murus*, *caseus*, *Colonia*).
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Borrowing from Latin continued after the fall of the Roman Empire during Christianisation, mediated by the church and monasteries.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Another important influx of Latin words can be observed during Renaissance humanism.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] In a scholarly context, the borrowings from Latin have continued until today, in the last few decades often indirectly through borrowings from English.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] During the 15th to 17th centuries, the influence of Italian was great, leading to many Italian loanwords in the fields of architecture, finance and music.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] The influence of the French language in the 17th to 19th centuries resulted in an even greater import of French words.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] The English influence was already present in the 19th century, but it did not become dominant until the second half of the 20th century.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Thus, Notker Labeo translated the Aristotelian treatises into pure (Old High) German in the decades after the year 1000.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] The tradition of loan translation revitalised in the 17th and 18th century with poets like Philipp von Zesen or linguists like Joachim Heinrich Campe, who introduced close to 300 words, which are still used in modern German.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Even today, there are movements that promote the substitution of foreign words that are deemed unnecessary with German alternatives.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] As in other Germanic languages, there are many pairs of synonyms due to the enrichment of the Germanic vocabulary with loanwords from Latin and Latinised Greek.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] These words often have different connotations from their Germanic counterparts and are usually perceived as more scholarly.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] The size of the vocabulary of German is difficult to estimate.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] The *Deutsches Wörterbuch* (*German Dictionary*), initiated by the Brothers Grimm (Jacob and Wilhelm Grimm) and the most comprehensive guide to the vocabulary of the German language, already contained over 330,000 headwords in its first edition.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] The modern German scientific vocabulary is estimated at nine million words and word groups (based on the analysis of 35 million sentences of a corpus in Leipzig, which as of July 2003 included 500 million words in total).
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] The German language is used in German literature and can be traced back to the Romans and Germania.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] German literature developed extensively during Middle Ages, with the most notable authors of the period being Walther von der Vogelweide and Wolfram von Eschenbach.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] The *Nibelungenlied*, whose author remains unknown, is also an important work of the epoch.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] The fairy tales collected and published by Jacob and Wilhelm Grimm in the 19th century became famous throughout the world.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Reformer and theologian Martin Luther, who translated the Bible into High German (a regional group of German varieties at southern and therefore *higher* regions), is widely credited for attributed to the basis for the modern Standard German language.
[src:apple-wine/german-language-p02] Among the best-known poets and authors in German are Lessing, Goethe, Schiller, Kleist, Hoffmann, Brecht, Heine and Kafka.
